<subSubSection id="14E2D8A6314869C5233FBB974D870FC9" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="generic diagnosis">
<paragraph id="E8954C2397B27C4C551D5008C06A65F2" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Generic diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5880457BBD30CE4ACB1D4F09C603A1D5" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
Among 
<taxonomicName id="48464490D544A0158188821182704805" authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1869" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="tribe" tribe="Phaeogenini">Phaeogenini</taxonomicName>
genera, 
<taxonomicName id="C36AF99168C925AEBBE720E0875C2167" authorityName="Wesmael" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="7C5D06CA694DFB21F9EEA28B2B7C7E31" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily recognized by a combination of the following: unidentate, falciform mandible; epistomal suture distinct; basal flagellomeres slender and elongate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8DA771B0BF77A2D4408A57E3C58661F5" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Unpublished illustration of Heterischnus huardi (Provancher) lateral habitus and frontal view of head by Professor Masaaki Tokunaga or his assistants, commissioned by Dr. Henry Townes." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.85.67792.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/583736" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">1</figureCitation>
); scutellum moderately narrow, convex, and distinctly elevated above metanotum; areolet (cell 1-2Rs) of the fore wing is closed (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="68F2D4E1420E002BD87A71FD4FC98DB9" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Unpublished illustration of Heterischnus huardi (Provancher) lateral habitus and frontal view of head by Professor Masaaki Tokunaga or his assistants, commissioned by Dr. Henry Townes." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.85.67792.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/583736" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">1</figureCitation>
); hind coxa simple; thyridium wide. In some species, notably 
<taxonomicName id="4CE6A6240274DF87EE1FD65B8179E217" baseAuthorityName="Provancher" baseAuthorityYear="1875" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus huardi" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huardi">
<emphasis id="AA014BE06DFA96A2E385F4519A250C84" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus huardi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Provancher), the clypeus is medially truncate with acute sublateral projections making such species instantly recognizable as 
<taxonomicName id="2499A77BD3713C99E90E7C38245E2A7A" authorityName="Wesmael" authorityYear="1859" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CE713AA5AB5B8C234C323A621F3F4011" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, the ventral clypeal margin varies between the aforementioned morphology and being medially straight without acute sublateral projections. The majority of species tend toward the latter condition. Additionally, the tarsal claws of 
<taxonomicName id="A06D40FEF35D014DDC7C1C4F6C7AA9E2" baseAuthorityName="O.F.Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Heterischnus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Heterischnus pulex" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulex">
<emphasis id="418868E6C1A7C3C9908EEBFC2F4AAC1F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Heterischnus pulex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken id="059455727D26B948D7A5A3445616E30F" originalValue="Müller">Mueller</normalizedToken>
) are pectinate which is unique among 
<taxonomicName id="B14519E797E1FE26E5023927BE8DCB5C" authorityName="Forster" authorityYear="1869" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="tribe" tribe="Phaeogenini">Phaeogenini</taxonomicName>
, although the tarsal claws are simple in the remaining species.
</paragraph>
